    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The Extrapolation Problem"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "RoPE encodes position m by rotating query and key vectors through angle mθᵢ in the i-th dimension pair. During training on sequences of length L_train = 2048, the model learns what angles in [0, 2048·θᵢ) mean for each dimension. At inference on length L_new = 8192, positions 2049..8191 produce angles the model has never encountered. Attention dot products land in untrained regions of angle space, attention entropy spikes or collapses, and perplexity degrades rapidly."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "This is the extrapolation problem. The naive fix — just feed in the longer sequence — does not work. The model's internal statistics were tuned for a specific range of (m-n) position differences, and anything beyond that range is out-of-distribution. Position Interpolation (PI), introduced by Chen et al. (2023), solves this by mapping all positions back into [0, L_train) before they ever reach the RoPE rotations."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Position interpolation compresses long positions into the trained range, whereas direct extrapolation sends positions out-of-distribution"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The Interpolation Fix"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The core idea is a one-line rescaling: before computing RoPE rotations, replace the token's absolute position m with m scaled by the ratio L_train / L_new."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "m' = m \\cdot \\frac{L_{\\text{train}}}{L_{\\text{new}}}"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "For a 4× context extension (2048 → 8192), every original position is divided by 4. Position 8191 becomes 2047.75 — fractional, but within the trained range. The RoPE rotation is now applied at a position the model has seen during training, so the angle is in-distribution."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The attention score between positions m and n depends only on (m - n) via RoPE's relative-position property. After interpolation, the maximum pairwise difference is at most (L_new - 1) × (L_train / L_new) ≈ L_train, which is the same bound the model saw at training. Extrapolation breaks this bound; interpolation preserves it."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Why Interpolation Beats Extrapolation Theoretically"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The bound on how much PI perturbs attention is provably small. For a RoPE-based attention head, the interpolated attention value differs from the ideal value by at most O(1/L_train) per token — a tiny perturbation that the model can recover from with modest fine-tuning. Extrapolation has no such bound; the model can be arbitrarily wrong on positions it has never seen."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Empirically: zero-shot (no fine-tuning) PI reduces perplexity at 8192 tokens from ~25 (direct extrapolation) to ~3.5 on LLaMA-7B, already within striking distance of the native 2048 perplexity of ~2.9. After 1 000 fine-tuning steps on long sequences, perplexity reaches ~2.97 — essentially matching the original."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Implementation"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "PI is a minimal code change: pass scaled positions to the RoPE rotation rather than the raw token indices."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import torch\nimport torch.nn as nn\nimport math\n\n\nclass RoPE(nn.Module):\n    \"\"\"Standard RoPE, position-interpolation-aware.\"\"\"\n\n    def __init__(self, dim: int, base: int = 10_000,\n                 max_train_len: int = 2048, scale: float = 1.0):\n        super().__init__()\n        self.scale = scale                       # L_new / L_train\n        inv_freq = 1.0 / (base ** (torch.arange(0, dim, 2).float() / dim))\n        self.register_buffer(\"inv_freq\", inv_freq)\n        self._cos_cached = self._sin_cached = None\n        self.max_train_len = max_train_len\n\n    def _build_cache(self, seq_len: int, device):\n        # Core of PI: divide positions by scale before RoPE.\n        t = torch.arange(seq_len, device=device).float() / self.scale\n        freqs = torch.outer(t, self.inv_freq)   # (seq_len, dim/2)\n        emb   = torch.cat([freqs, freqs], dim=-1)\n        self._cos_cached = emb.cos()[None, None, :, :]  # (1, 1, T, dim)\n        self._sin_cached = emb.sin()[None, None, :, :]\n\n    def forward(self, q: torch.Tensor, k: torch.Tensor):\n        # q, k: (batch, heads, seq_len, dim)\n        seq_len = q.shape[2]\n        if (self._cos_cached is None\n                or self._cos_cached.shape[2] < seq_len):\n            self._build_cache(seq_len, q.device)\n        cos = self._cos_cached[:, :, :seq_len, :]\n        sin = self._sin_cached[:, :, :seq_len, :]\n        return apply_rotary(q, cos, sin), apply_rotary(k, cos, sin)\n\n\ndef apply_rotary(x: torch.Tensor, cos, sin):\n    \"\"\"Rotate x using precomputed cos/sin tables.\"\"\"\n    half = x.shape[-1] // 2\n    x1, x2 = x[..., :half], x[..., half:]\n    return torch.cat([x1 * cos[..., :half] - x2 * sin[..., :half],\n                      x1 * sin[..., half:] + x2 * cos[..., half:]], dim=-1)\n\n\n# Usage: extending LLaMA-2 (L_train=4096) to 16 384 tokens\n# scale = 16384 / 4096 = 4.0\nrope = RoPE(dim=128, base=10_000, max_train_len=4096, scale=4.0)\n\n# Then fine-tune for ~1 000 steps on long sequences.\n# That's all PI requires."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The Fine-Tuning Recipe"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "PI zero-shot already works, but a short fine-tuning run closes the remaining perplexity gap completely:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Dataset: a small subset of the original pretraining data (or any long-document corpus), sampled at the new target length."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Steps: 1 000 gradient update steps — two orders of magnitude less than the original pretraining."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Learning rate: typically 2×10⁻⁵, matching the final pretraining LR or slightly lower."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Batch: at least 64 examples of length L_new to give the model enough long-range signal per step."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The reason so few steps are needed is that PI does not change the structure of the model at all — it only re-maps positions. The model has all the capacity to handle long contexts; it just needs to recalibrate the slightly different position values PI produces."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Limitations and Variants"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Linear PI compresses position differences uniformly across all frequency dimensions. High-frequency RoPE dimensions (small θᵢ, pairs near index 0) represent fine-grained local structure. Scaling them down by the same factor as low-frequency dimensions can blur local patterns that the model relies on."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "NTK-aware interpolation (\"neural tangent kernel\") addresses this by scaling the RoPE base frequency instead of the positions directly:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "\\theta_i^{\\text{new}} = \\frac{1}{\\left(\\text{base} \\cdot s^{d/(d-2)}\\right)^{2i/d}}, \\quad s = \\frac{L_{\\text{new}}}{L_{\\text{train}}}"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "This effectively leaves high-frequency dimensions nearly unchanged (they already cycle fast enough) while interpolating low-frequency dimensions that represent global position. YaRN refines this further with dimension-specific correction factors, achieving state-of-the-art results used in LLaMA 3.1's 128k context."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Linear PI remains the conceptual foundation. The variants (NTK, YaRN) all inherit the core insight: scale positions into [0, L_train) rather than letting them run beyond it, because interpolation is provably safer than extrapolation."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
